\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces Three coordination regimes between the ASR and MT vLLM engines sharing a single GPU. Box widths sketch realistic wall-clock durations under MT heavier than ASR (Gemma\nobreakspace  {}4B vs.\ Qwen\nobreakspace  {}1.7B). In (a), ASR runs at a fixed audio cadence and appends to a shared source prefix; a single MT decode runs at a time and is relaunched on completion over the current state of that prefix, so successive MT prompts can differ substantially in length, undermining the continuity assumption of \textsc  {LocalAgreement}-style emission policies. In (b), MT is pipelined at the ASR chunk cadence; the MT lane is contiguous because MT is GPU-constrained to one decode at a time and is heavier than ASR. In (c), ASR and MT alternate strictly; this is our IWSLT\nobreakspace  {}2026 configuration and the one reported in Table\nobreakspace  {}\ref  {tab:e2e}.\relax }}{8}{figure.caption.14}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:coord-regimes}{{7}{8}{Three coordination regimes between the ASR and MT vLLM engines sharing a single GPU. Box widths sketch realistic wall-clock durations under MT heavier than ASR (Gemma~4B vs.\ Qwen~1.7B). In (a), ASR runs at a fixed audio cadence and appends to a shared source prefix; a single MT decode runs at a time and is relaunched on completion over the current state of that prefix, so successive MT prompts can differ substantially in length, undermining the continuity assumption of \textsc {LocalAgreement}-style emission policies. In (b), MT is pipelined at the ASR chunk cadence; the MT lane is contiguous because MT is GPU-constrained to one decode at a time and is heavier than ASR. In (c), ASR and MT alternate strictly; this is our IWSLT~2026 configuration and the one reported in Table~\ref {tab:e2e}.\relax }{figure.caption.14}{}}
